<div id="review_2913407112" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2913407112" />
    <a title="Eric" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/17125495-eric"><img alt="Eric" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1609167065p2/17125495.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2913407112?book_show_action=true">Aug 06, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Eric" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Eric" href="/user/show/17125495-eric">Eric</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2913407112" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17304761821852458873">Not quite as dramatic as the first book of this trilogy, but again, well written. Being a middle book, it ebbs and flows like an impatient stream itching to reach a river. Eventually, we get to the river, which is book three.<br/><br/>The author, in his acknowledgements calls <i>Memory, Sorrow, and Thorn</i> a bloated epic. A classic epic it is of good versus evil. Lots of characters, places and individual struggles to follow. So follow I will and onto book three, <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/28691.To_Green_Angel_Tower__Memory__Sorrow__and_Thorn___3_' title='To Green Angel Tower (Memory, Sorrow, and Thorn, #3) by Tad Williams' rel='nofollow noopener'>
