    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3484064278" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3484064278" />
    <a title="Doug" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/33038913-doug"><img alt="Doug" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1608679828p2/33038913.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3484064278?book_show_action=true">Aug 19, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Doug" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Doug" href="/user/show/33038913-doug">Doug</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3484064278" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12356536548487296892">This book basically captures the worst parts of middle-book syndrome: it&apos;s more of unrewarding slog than it had any right to be, because the underlying plot and characters are really quite good. But they are packaged here in a way that is really... unfortunate for the reader.<br/><br/>The whole plot revolves around getting to the Stone of Farewell, and this plot is just stretched way too thin. It doesn&apos;t help that the author is holding every single card close to his vest, and it gets really frustrating to</span>
  <span id="freeText12356536548487296892" style="display:none">This book basically captures the worst parts of middle-book syndrome: it's more of unrewarding slog than it had any right to be, because the underlying plot and characters are really quite good. But they are packaged here in a way that is really... unfortunate for the reader.<br /><br />The whole plot revolves around getting to the Stone of Farewell, and this plot is just stretched way too thin. It doesn't help that the author is holding every single card close to his vest, and it gets really frustrating to not get any answers. This problem is exacerbated by the fact that I desperately wanted some reason to get excited about what's coming, in order to feel like this slog was justified. Ultimately, the answer to whether it was justified will sadly come only in the last book. If this book had been a third, or even a quarter, of the length, or simply not existed at all and its contents consolidated into the preceding or following book, I think this series would have been an excellent duology. But the pacing here sucks, which is a shame because everything else is so cool.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12356536548487296892" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


